# Facial Recognition using Convolutional Neural Networks

A comparative study of deep learning strategies for facial recognition on a limited dataset.

## Project Overview

This project implements and compares **4 CNN architectures** for facial recognition:
- Custom CNN (built from scratch)
- VGG-16 (transfer learning)
- ResNet50 (transfer learning)
- InceptionV3 / GoogleNet (transfer learning)

The goal was to evaluate the trade-offs between training from scratch vs. transfer learning on a small, high-variance dataset.

## Dataset

**"5 Faces Dataset"** — Ankush Kuwar (Kaggle)
- ~750 images across 5 celebrity classes
- Classes: Bill Gates, Jack Ma, Narendra Modi, Elon Musk, Donald Trump
- ~130 images per class
- License: CC0 (Public Domain)
- [Dataset link](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ankushkunwar7777/5-face)

## Results

| Model | Validation Accuracy | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Custom CNN | 83.90% | Unstable training, 50 epochs |
| VGG-16 | ~88% | Smooth convergence |
| ResNet50 | <40% | Failed — too deep for small dataset |
| **InceptionV3** | **95.76%** | ✅ Best model |

## Key Findings

- **Transfer learning outperforms** training from scratch on limited data
- **InceptionV3's multi-scale Inception Modules** are best suited for facial details
- **ResNet50 fails** on small datasets — complexity must match data size
- **Custom CNN is viable** but requires careful tuning and data augmentation

## Methodology

### 1. Face Localization
Haar Cascade Classifiers (OpenCV) used to detect and crop face regions → resized to 128×128×3.

### 2. Preprocessing
- Pixel normalization: [0, 255] → [0, 1]
- 80/20 train/test split (stratified)
- Data augmentation: rotation, zoom, horizontal flip (ImageDataGenerator)

### 3. Architecture Strategy
- **Custom CNN**: 3 conv blocks (32→64→128 filters) + BatchNorm + Dropout(0.5)
- **Transfer Learning**: Frozen pre-trained base + Global Average Pooling + Dense head
- **Optimizer**: Adam, lr=0.0001
- **Loss**: Categorical Cross-Entropy

